But though in the first Book of Tacitus
his History they are both compared as like, in opposition to a good Prince; yet in his second book they are opposed the one to the other as unlike, with notes of distinction. Vitellii ignavae voluptates, Othonis flagrantissimae libidines. Vitellius ventre & gulâ sibi ipsi hostis;
Vitellius a Drunkard and Glutton, Otho a wanton and licentious liver. Otho luxi • , saevitiâ, audaciâ, Reipublicae exitiosior ducebatur; of the one side, an ill mind in a man of nothing, and of the other, an ill mind joyned with courage and edge.

